var CATS=[
  {id:"sprint",label:"Sprint Work",color:"#E74C3C",icon:"S",freq:"1x/week (800m); early only (1600/3200m)",why:"Develops neuromuscular speed and fast-twitch fiber recruitment. In his warm-up article, Davis writes that mobility exercises and sprint drills 'kick-start your fast-twitch fibers and use the stretch-shortening cycle in muscles and tendons to return energy from the ground, which are both necessary when running fast.' Hill sprints build posterior-chain power. The training document recommends hill sprints and accelerations can be done after easy runs or after threshold/sub-T workouts. Flying 30s should not be done the day before a race-specific workout.",presets:["4-6x10s very steep hill 85-100%","6-8x10s steep hill 85-100%","5x100m accels last 25m at mile/800/400/max","4-5x30m flying max","6-8x30m flying max"],refs:[{t:"Getting the warm-up right",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2014/09/getting-warm-up-right.html"}]},
  {id:"faster800",label:"Faster-than-800m",color:"#E67E22",icon:"F",freq:"1x/10-14 days (800m); rare (1600/3200m)",why:"Builds speed reserve by running faster than 800m race pace. These reps are far above critical speed, heavily depleting D-prime. Davis describes D-prime as 'a finite energy resource: when running faster than your critical speed, your body only has a certain amount of energy it can produce before you go bankrupt and have to stop.' Long rest (4-8 min) allows substantial reconstitution. Davis cites research suggesting D-prime reconstitutes with a half-life of about 4-5 minutes.",presets:["4-6x150m at 400m pace w/ 4-5 min","6-8x200m at 105% 800m pace w/ 3-4 min","4x300m at 95% 400m pace w/ 6-8 min","400m race or 4x400 relay"],refs:[{t:"Critical speed guide",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/01/critical-speed-guide-for-runners.html"},{t:"Post-race workouts",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2025/12/post-race-workouts.html"}]},
  {id:"800pace",label:"800m Pace",color:"#F39C12",icon:"8",freq:"Every 7-10 days (spec); 10-15 (non-spec)",why:"Race-specific work for the 800m. 800m pace is well above critical speed, producing what Davis calls a metabolically unsustainable state. In his SSmax article, he explains that at these speeds, VO2 steadily rises until it hits VO2max, blood lactate spirals upward, and muscle fibers progressively lose efficiency, forcing recruitment of additional fast-twitch fibers. On post-race workouts after an 800m, Davis writes the workout should provide 'a different kind of stimulus than the race itself.'",presets:["12x200m at 800m pace w/ walk+jog","8x300m at 800m pace w/ 2-3 min","2-3 sets 400-300-200 at 98-100-102%","3x500m at 98-100% 800m w/ 6-8 min","800m race or 4x800 relay"],refs:[{t:"Steady-state max (SSmax)",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/08/steady-state-max-for-runners.html"},{t:"Post-race workouts",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2025/12/post-race-workouts.html"}]},
  {id:"1600pace",label:"1600m Pace",color:"#D4A017",icon:"16",freq:"Every 7-10 days (spec); 10-15 (non-spec)",why:"Mile pace is above critical speed, so D-prime is being depleted throughout. Davis notes 'racing a mile is a classic case where post-race workouts make a lot of sense' because 'the mile just is not that much volume, and milers often need a steady supply of endurance work to keep their aerobic fitness up.' Post-race guidelines: 60-80% of normal volume, 25-50% longer recovery, 2-4% slower paces.",presets:["16x200m at mile pace w/ 200m jog","3-4 sets 400-300-200 at 100-102-104%","8-10x400m at mile pace w/ 2 min","6-8x500m at mile w/ 2 min","5-6x600m at mile w/ 3 min","4-6x200m add-on","1600m race"],refs:[{t:"Post-race workouts",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2025/12/post-race-workouts.html"}]},
  {id:"3200pace",label:"3200m Pace",color:"#2ECC71",icon:"32",freq:"Every 7-10 days (spec); 10-15 (non-spec)",why:"3200m pace is above critical speed but D-prime depletes more slowly than at mile pace. Descending sets (1000-800-600) simulate finishing strong. Per Davis, after a 3200m race, endurance-focused post-race work complements the race stimulus. He emphasizes choosing the opposite kind of stimulus.",presets:["12-16x300m at 3200m pace w/ 100m jog","2 sets 5x500m w/ 1 min / 5 min","6-8x600m w/ 2-3 min","5-6x800m w/ 3-4 min","2 sets 1000-800-600 at 98-100-102%","3200m race"],refs:[{t:"Post-race workouts",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2025/12/post-race-workouts.html"}]},
  {id:"5kpace",label:"5k / VO2max",color:"#27AE60",icon:"5k",freq:"Every 10-14 days",why:"In Davis's analysis of over 1,300 critical speed estimates, VO2max pace (CS+) corresponds to approximately 100% of 5k pace. At this speed you are above critical speed, in the metabolically unsustainable zone. Davis explains that VO2 steadily rises until hitting VO2max, and muscle fibers progressively lose efficiency. Training here drives oxygen consumption toward its ceiling. Short rest (1.5-4 min) keeps heart rate elevated.",presets:["8-10x600m at 5k w/ 1.5 min","6-8x800m at 5k w/ 2-3 min","6x1k at 5k w/ 3 min","4-5x1200m at 5k w/ 3-4 min"],refs:[{t:"Threshold, CV, VO2max from 5k",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/11/threshold-cv-vo2max-from-5k.html"},{t:"Steady-state max (SSmax)",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/08/steady-state-max-for-runners.html"}]},
  {id:"cv",label:"CV / CS Pace",color:"#3498DB",icon:"CV",freq:"Every 10-14 days (1600/3200); weekly early (800m)",why:"Davis's analysis places critical speed (CS) at approximately 96% of 5k pace -- the boundary between metabolically sustainable and unsustainable running. He writes that critical speed is 'increasingly becoming the gold standard among physiologists for identifying the limit of what runners would call high-end aerobic or steady-state running speeds.' Training right around this boundary expands the pace you can sustain aerobically.",presets:["10-14x2 min at CS w/ 1 min jog","6-7x3 min at CS w/ 1.5 min","5-6x4 min at CS w/ 2 min","2 sets 8x1.5 min w/ 30s / 3-4 min"],refs:[{t:"Critical speed guide",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/01/critical-speed-guide-for-runners.html"},{t:"Threshold, CV, VO2max from 5k",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/11/threshold-cv-vo2max-from-5k.html"}]},
  {id:"threshold",label:"Threshold & Sub-T",color:"#8E44AD",icon:"LT",freq:"Weekly (1600/3200m); weekly early (800m)",why:"Davis writes that 'the single biggest determinant of your performance in long-distance events is your pace at your maximal metabolic steady-state, or SSmax.' His analysis places threshold pace (CS-) at approximately 90% of 5k pace. He notes LT2 is the most familiar estimate of SSmax but 'can only estimate your true SSmax within about ten percent or so.' The training document notes HS runners exhibit 'aerobic drift' where aerobic development lags behind speed; consistent threshold work closes this gap.",presets:["7-9x3 min threshold w/ 1 min jog","5-7x4 min threshold w/ 1 min jog","3x8 min sub-T w/ 2 min walk","10+8+6 min progressive sub-T"],refs:[{t:"Threshold, CV, VO2max from 5k",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/11/threshold-cv-vo2max-from-5k.html"},{t:"Steady-state max (SSmax)",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/08/steady-state-max-for-runners.html"}]},
  {id:"aerobic",label:"General Aerobic",color:"#1ABC9C",icon:"AE",freq:"Weekly early (1600/3200); none (800m)",why:"Builds your aerobic foundation. At moderate effort, all key metabolic metrics are stable over time -- what Davis defines as a metabolic steady-state. In his SSmax article, he shows that VO2, heart rate, blood lactate, intramuscular pH, and phosphocreatine all plateau and remain stable. Training in this zone develops capillary density, mitochondrial volume, and slow-twitch fiber endurance.",presets:["45-60 min moderate","30 min easy out, progressive back","25-40 min easy + 3x9 min sub-T w/ 3 min float","30-50 min easy + 20 min progressive"],refs:[{t:"Steady-state max (SSmax)",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/08/steady-state-max-for-runners.html"}]},
  {id:"easy",label:"Easy / Maintenance",color:"#7CB342",icon:"E",hasRunMode:true,freq:"Non-workout days",why:"Recovery and maintenance runs promote blood flow, build aerobic adaptations at low stress, and strengthen bones, tendons, and ligaments. In his cool-down article, Davis writes that for young runners, structured running 'helps reinforce the notion that practice generally, and workout/race days specifically, are comprised of a structure of things that we do every time, no matter what.' The training document notes HS runners need more maintenance runs vs. true recovery.",presets:["Easy run","Moderate run","Easy to moderate","Recovery run","Maintenance run","45-55 min maintenance"],refs:[{t:"Getting the cool-down right",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2022/05/getting-cool-down-right.html"}]},
  {id:"longrun",label:"Long Run",color:"#558B2F",icon:"LR",hasRunMode:true,freq:"Weekly (1600/3200m); bi-weekly (800m)",why:"The long run builds aerobic endurance, capillary density, mitochondrial volume, and mental toughness for sustained effort. For high schoolers, long runs should progress from easy to moderate -- not slow slogs. Davis notes that HS runners benefit more from moderate-effort maintenance-style running than true easy pace. Progressive long runs and long runs with sub-threshold segments are especially effective for 1600/3200m runners.",presets:["50-60 min easy","55-65 min easy to moderate","60-70 min with last 20 min progressive","45-55 min easy + 3x9 min sub-T w/ 3 min float","50-65 min through rolling hills","40-50 min easy + 15 min progressive finish","55-70 min moderate long run"]},
  {id:"prerace",label:"Pre-Race Day",color:"#26A69A",icon:"PR",freq:"Day before meet",why:"Davis writes strides should be 'progressively-paced, moving from somewhat slower than race pace in the initial strides to somewhat faster than race pace in the final stride.' He also writes 'the single biggest mistake most runners make with their race-day warm-up is include too much down-time.'",presets:["Shorter run + strides","Easy-mod + strides","Short easy (800m pre-race)","Easy + 2x200m at race pace","Easy + accelerations"],refs:[{t:"Getting the warm-up right",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2014/09/getting-warm-up-right.html"}]},
  {id:"meet",label:"Meet / Race Day",color:"#0D47A1",icon:"M",freq:"As scheduled",why:"Davis prescribes: 12-15 min progressing easy to strong, dynamic drills, then progressively faster strides. He recommends a 2-3 min threshold segment before distance races. On post-race workouts, the workout should be 'a different kind of stimulus than the race itself.' Guidelines: 60-80% volume, 25-50% longer recovery, 2-4% slower paces because 'all-out races necessarily cause some muscle damage that is going to hurt your running economy.'",presets:["Meet: standard warmup","Meet: accels for 800m/400m","Meet: doubling protocol","Meet: 2nd race cooldown","Post-race: threshold/CV 50-60%","Post-race: 200m reps at 3200m pace","Post-race fartlek","Time trial","JV meet","Invitational"],refs:[{t:"Getting the warm-up right",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2014/09/getting-warm-up-right.html"},{t:"Post-race workouts",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2025/12/post-race-workouts.html"}]},
  {id:"evaluation",label:"Evaluation",color:"#F9A825",icon:"EV",freq:"Early season",why:"The critical speed model has two parameters: CS and D-prime. Davis explains athletes with higher D-prime relative to CS are 'more speed-oriented, and thus have different strengths and weaknesses.' He notes D-prime 'is not correlated with your proportion of fast-twitch glycolytic (type IIx) muscle fibers' but 'does map pretty well onto common ideas about training for fast-twitch vs. slow-twitch athletes.'",presets:["1600m TT + flying 200m","4x400 relay at JV meet","Flying 30m with photogates","Race 4x400m eval"],refs:[{t:"Critical speed guide",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2024/01/critical-speed-guide-for-runners.html"}]},
  {id:"rest",label:"Rest / Off",color:"#78909C",icon:"R",why:"In his biomechanical training load article, Davis explains: 'Every time you take a step during a run, the load-bearing tissues in your body experience a cyclical mechanical load.' Each cycle causes 'a tiny amount of tissue damage,' and 'if damage accumulates faster than your body can repair it, the result is an overuse injury.' He compares this to bending a paperclip until it breaks -- 'the exact same physical process.'",presets:["Full rest","Active recovery / walk","Optional shakeout"],refs:[{t:"Biomechanical training load",u:"https://runningwritings.com/2025/11/biomechanical-training-load-for-runners.html"}]},
  {id:"fartlek",label:"Fartlek",color:"#00897B",icon:"FK",freq:"Weekly to bi-weekly",why:"Fartlek ('speed play' in Swedish) blends continuous running with unstructured surges at varying paces. Unlike structured intervals, fartlek develops the ability to change pace mid-run -- a critical racing skill. Surges can target any pace zone (threshold, CV, VO2max) while the float recoveries keep heart rate elevated, building aerobic endurance. Fartlek is also excellent for teaching effort-based running rather than pace-dependent running.",presets:["6x2 min surge w/ 2 min float","8x1 min hard w/ 1 min easy","3 min-2 min-1 min x 3 sets w/ equal float","20 min continuous fartlek (30s hard/60s easy)","Ladder: 1-2-3-4-3-2-1 min w/ 1 min float","Moneghetti fartlek: 2x90s, 4x60s, 4x30s, 4x15s","Telephone pole fartlek (surge 2, float 1)","Progressive fartlek: 6x3 min getting faster"]},
  {id:"custom",label:"Custom",color:"#607D8B",icon:"C",freq:"As needed",why:"Use this for any workout that doesn't fit the standard categories -- cross-training, team activities, special sessions, or anything else you want to assign.",presets:["Custom workout","Cross-training","Pool running / aqua jog","Bike / elliptical","Core & strength circuit","Team activity","Film session","Stretching / yoga","Fundraiser / team building"]}
];


