/* ─── COACH REFERENCE (from John Davis training strategies document) ─── */
var COACH_REF={
sprint:{title:"Sprint Work",text:"Once per week for most of the season for 800m, once per week only in early season for 1600/3200m\n\n\u2022 4-6 x 10 sec up very steep hill at 85 >> 100% max speed\n\u2022 6-8 x 10 sec up steep hill at 85 >> 100% max speed\n\u2022 5 x 100m accelerations with last 25 meters at mile / 800 / 400 /max speed / max speed\n\u2022 (after a few accelerations): 4-5 x 30m flying at max speed (can cause soreness)\n  \u25CB Do initially on astroturf infield if possible\n\u2022 (after a few accelerations): 6-8 x 30m flying at max speed (can cause soreness)\n  \u25CB Do on track if athlete will be racing 400m or 800m\n\u2022 Can do these after easy runs OR after threshold / sub-T workouts\n  \u25CB Hill sprints and accelerations are fine the day before a workout, flying 30s should probably not be done the day before a race specific workout. Day before threshold or CV pace is fine though"},
faster800:{title:"Faster-than-800m Pace (~400m pace?)",text:"Once per 10\u201314 days in mid-season for 800m, rarely or not at all for 1600/3200m\n\n\u2022 4\u20136 x 150m at aggressive 400m pace w/ 4\u20135 min rest\n\u2022 6\u20138 x 200m at 105% 800m pace or ~400m pace w/ 3\u20134 min rest\n\u2022 4 x 300m at 95% 400m pace w/ 6\u20138 min rest\n\u2022 400m competition, 4 x 400m relay leg (possibly doubling back from 1600m or 800m)"},
"800pace":{title:"800m Pace",text:"Every 7\u201310 days for specialists, every 10\u201315 days for non-specialists\n\n\u2022 12 x 200m at 800m pace w/ 100m walk + 100m jog (or 2 min rest)\n\u2022 8 x 300m at 800m pace w/ 2-3 min walk\n\u2022 2-3 sets of 400-300-200 at 98-100-102% 800m pace, 3 min within sets and 5-7 min between sets\n\u2022 3 x 500m at 98-100% 800m pace w/ 6-8 min rest (toughest 800m specific session)\n\u2022 800m competition (possibly doubling back from 1600m), 4 x 800m relay leg"},
"1600pace":{title:"1600m Pace",text:"Every 7\u201310 days for specialists, every 10\u201315 days for non-specialists\n\n\u2022 16 x 200m at mile pace w/ 200m jog (or 1.5 min rest)\n\u2022 3-4 sets of 400-300-200 at 100-102-104% mile pace w/ 1.5 min rest and 3 min between sets\n\u2022 8-10 x 400m at mile pace w/ 2 min rest (I usually skip over this; high schoolers overdo 400m repeats)\n\u2022 6-8 x 500m at mile pace w/ 2 min rest\n\u2022 5-6 x 600m at mile pace w/ 3 min rest (pretty tough session)\n\u2022 Late season, can add 4\u20136 x 200m at mile pace to the end of other workouts\n\u2022 1600m competition"},
"3200pace":{title:"3200m Pace",text:"Every 7\u201310 days for specialists, every 10\u201315 days for non-specialists\n\n\u2022 12-16 x 300m at 3200m pace w/ 100m jog\n\u2022 2 sets of 5x500m at 3200m pace w/ 1 min walk and 5 min between sets\n\u2022 6-8 x 600m at 3200m pace w/ 2\u20133 min walk/jog rest\n\u2022 5-6 x 800m at 3200m pace w/ 3-4 min rest\n\u2022 2 sets of 1000-800-600m at 98-100-102% 3200m pace w/ 3 min rest and 6 min between sets\n\u2022 3200m competition (possibly doubling back from 1600m or 4x800m)"},
"5kpace":{title:"5k Pace / CS+ Pace",text:"Every 10\u201314 days early-season for 800m/1600m, every 10-14 days throughout season for 3200m\n\n\u2022 8-10 x 600m at 5k pace w/ 1.5 min rest\n\u2022 6\u20138 x 800m at 5k pace w/ 2\u20133 min rest\n\u2022 6 x 1k at 5k pace w/ 3 min rest\n\u2022 4-5 x 1200m at 5k pace w/ 3\u20134 min rest"},
cv:{title:"8k/10k/CS Pace / CV Pace",text:"Every 10-14 days throughout season if possible for 1600/3200, weekly in early season for 800m (can substitute for threshold/sub-T)\n\n\u2022 10\u201314 x 2 min at CS w/ 1 min jog\n\u2022 6\u20137 x 3 min at CS w/ 1.5 min jog\n\u2022 5-6 x 4 min at CS w/ 2 min jog\n\u2022 2 sets of 8x1.5 min at CS w/ 30sec walk and 3\u20134 min between sets"},
threshold:{title:"Threshold (CS- / SSmax) and Sub-threshold",text:"Weekly throughout season for 1600/3200m if possible; weekly in early season for 800m\n\n\u2022 7-9 x 3 min at threshold w/ 1 min jog\n\u2022 5-7 x 4 min at threshold w/ 1 min jog\n\u2022 3 x 8 min at 'sub-T' (~86-88% 5k) w/ 2 min walk (difficult to pace correctly, use early season if needed on the roads)\n\u2022 10 + 8 + 6 min progressive sub-threshold w/ 2 min walk, from 86% >> 90% 5k pace"},
aerobic:{title:"General High-end Aerobic Workouts",text:"Weekly during early season for 1600/3200, not at all for 800m\n\n\u2022 45-60 min moderate run, possibly through rolling hills\n\u2022 30 min easy 'out', then progressive run back aiming to finish several minutes faster\n\u2022 25\u201340 min easy + 3 x 9 minutes at sub-threshold w/ 3 min moderate 'float' (as a long run day)\n\u2022 30\u201350 min easy, then 20 min progressive finish"},
easy:{title:"Non-workout Days",text:"In terms of non-workout days, you will find that high schoolers need more 'conditioning runs' or 'maintenance runs', i.e. easy progressing to moderate type runs, or moderate the whole way, as opposed to true recovery runs at a very easy pace.\n\n\u2022 Part of this is that when you are not in great shape because you didn't train all winter, there is no such thing as a recovery run! Everything is some flavor of moderate, in effect\n\u2022 Another part is that as you progress in your career, you move towards bigger stress and bigger recovery. Adults can often do very high volume and high-quality workouts, e.g. 20 mi at 95% MP or 4-3-2-1k at 10k >> 5k pace, both sessions would be extreme overreach for a high schooler\n  \u25CB Conversely the adult needs VERY easy recovery, often 3\u20135 days, after such tough sessions\n\u2022 For a high schooler, and especially younger high schoolers, you need a 'flatter' distribution of intensity in the week\n  \u25CB Better to do a few low volume sessions every week vs. really hammer one big one\n  \u25CB e.g. contrast adult who might do 10x1k at threshold Monday and 4x2k at 8k pace Thursday with a very easy and an easy run in between\n  \u25CB vs. high schooler who might do 6 x 1k Monday, and 10x2min at 8k pace ('CV') on Wednesday, with a 45-55 min maintenance run at more of a moderate effort on Tuesday.\n\n\u2022 You can also mirror this progression in the season itself. Early in the season you want a flatter distribution of intensity; late season when you do race-specific workouts and races, you can take more true easy / recovery days"},
longrun:{title:"Long Run",text:"From the General High-end Aerobic Workouts section (weekly during early season for 1600/3200, not at all for 800m):\n\n\u2022 45-60 min moderate run, possibly through rolling hills\n\u2022 30 min easy 'out', then progressive run back aiming to finish several minutes faster\n\u2022 25\u201340 min easy + 3 x 9 minutes at sub-threshold w/ 3 min moderate 'float' (as a long run day)\n\u2022 30\u201350 min easy, then 20 min progressive finish\n\nKey context from Davis:\n\u2022 High schoolers need more 'conditioning runs' or 'maintenance runs', i.e. easy progressing to moderate type runs, or moderate the whole way, as opposed to true recovery runs at a very easy pace\n\u2022 For a high schooler, and especially younger high schoolers, you need a 'flatter' distribution of intensity in the week. Better to do a few low volume sessions every week vs. really hammer one big one"},
prerace:{title:"Pre-Race Day",text:"Recommend a shorter run than normal, except early season for 1600/3200m where you can do a standard easy to moderate run and strides.\n\n\u2022 Can help to do something like 2 x 200m at race pace but that's mostly for getting the pace dialed in, vs. any physical benefit\n\u2022 Don't think you need too much different for 800m vs 1600/3200, aside from maybe doing a shorter run for 800m pre-race, and maybe a few accelerations"},
meet:{title:"Meet / Race Day",text:"Meet day:\n\u2022 Standard warmup for first race, no matter how many you are doing\n  \u25CB Usually 12 min easy + strides and maybe a 1.5-2 min segment at ~8k effort\n  \u25CB Can also add accelerations for 800m or 400m\n  \u25CB See also: https://runningwritings.com/2014/09/getting-warm-up-right.html\n\u2022 If doubling: 5\u20136 min easy cooldown, rest and have high-carb snacks in interim period\n\u2022 Second race warmup: 8 min progressive and 3-4 strides and/or accelerations (if racing 800/400m)\n\u2022 Second race cool-down: 6\u201310 min easy\n\nCool downs generally:\n\u2022 Unless racing again the same day, try to have them be 10\u201315 min of 'real' running (not a slogging jog) to get some true aerobic benefit\n\u2022 Early season, consider post-race workout \u2013 for more advanced runners\n  \u25CB Basically idea is to get more than just (say) 1600m of quality in on the day\n  \u25CB Usually do something 'opposite' of what the race was. Examples:\n  \u25CB Race a 1600m, do threshold or CV pace \u2013 usually 50\u201360% of a 'full workout' volume (e.g. can do 5 x 3 min at threshold w/ 1 min jog). You'll need to adjust the pace a bit, threshold pace can be a few percent slower after a race since you're fatigued\n  \u25CB Race an 800m, can do some 200m repeats at 3200m pace w/ 200m jog or a 1.5-2 min walk.\n    \u25CB May need to get inventive with how you do these, e.g. from 100m to 300m along the backstretch in outside lanes when other events are going, or can do it as 30 sec / 1.5 min fartlek outside the track completely\n\nWhy warmups are important:\n\u2022 You will run better when fully warmed up, especially with a more rigorous warmup than 'jog a few minutes and do some half-hearted strides' \u2013 there is good science on this.\n\u2022 Related: https://runnersconnect.net/the-scientifically-recommended-warm-up-for-running/\n\nWhy cooldowns are important:\n\u2022 It really does flush out lactate more effectively than standing around, and in practice people tend to feel terrible the next day if they run hard and then take NO cooldown\n\u2022 Also more practically we need a real aerobic stimulus to balance out the anaerobic stimulus of the race. If you do 10min warmup, a few strides, and race an 800m and you don't cool down, you're barely at two miles of volume for the day! That just is not going to cut it.\n  \u25CB Also hence the reason for real running pace on cooldown, not just jogging around\n\u2022 Related: https://runningwritings.com/2022/05/getting-cool-down-right.html"},
evaluation:{title:"Evaluating Mid vs. Long Distance Potential",text:"\u2022 1600m time trial, then 6\u201310 min rest, then 'flying' 200m (i.e. with a running start) can be good for evaluating potential. Can just rank-order people by 1600 vs 200m time and see who does well relative to others (e.g. top X percentile).\n\u2022 If the sprint team has photogates, you can borrow them one day when you are doing flying 30m reps and see whose top speed is best.\n  \u25CB At Edina we spotted a few future 52.x-50.x 400m runners in the distance group this way\n\u2022 Can have athletes run 4 x 400m relay legs at a JV meet or an invitational with a B-section of 4x400 \u2013 just 'flood' the entries with lots of teams and have basically everyone who didn't do 3200m do the 4x400.\n\u2022 Can do some ad-hoc work like having a 5:40 miler do mile pace repeats with someone doing CV pace at 5:40/mi, or similar stuff \u2013 as needed / desired, can get a little chaotic but good for giving younger promising runners the experience of running with the faster older runners"},
rest:{title:"Rest / Recovery",text:"In his biomechanical training load article, Davis explains: 'Every time you take a step during a run, the load-bearing tissues in your body experience a cyclical mechanical load.' Each cycle causes 'a tiny amount of tissue damage,' and 'if damage accumulates faster than your body can repair it, the result is an overuse injury.' He compares this to bending a paperclip until it breaks \u2013 'the exact same physical process.'"},
_season:{title:"Season Periodization",text:"These workout volumes are roughly appropriate for juniors/seniors who have done several seasons before but are not doing super high volume, adjust down (or up) as needed.\n\nProbably most helpful to frame it in terms of main, secondary, and tertiary emphasis at different points in the season.\n\n1600/3200m Training Emphasis:\n\nEarly season:\n\u2022 Main: Easy to moderate mileage, general aerobic workouts\n\u2022 Secondary: Threshold, sub-threshold, and CV pace\n\u2022 Tertiary: Hill sprints, 5k pace, initial 1600/3200m pace workout\n\nMid-season:\n\u2022 Main: Threshold and CV pace\n\u2022 Secondary: Easy to moderate mileage, 5k pace, intermediate 1600/3200m workouts and races\n\u2022 Tertiary: 800m pace, hill sprints, accelerations, maybe flying 30s\n\nLate-season:\n\u2022 Main: 1600/3200 workouts and races\n\u2022 Secondary: 5k pace, CV pace, threshold\n\u2022 Tertiary: Easy to moderate mileage, 800m pace, accelerations\n\n\n800m Training Emphasis:\n\nEarly season:\n\u2022 Main: Threshold and CV pace, Initial 5k pace workouts (as 'aerobic base'), hill sprints\n\u2022 Secondary: initial 800m workouts, easy to moderate mileage\n\u2022 Tertiary: Initial 1600m workouts\n\nMid-season:\n\u2022 Main: Initial and intermediate 400m workouts, intermediate 800m workouts and races\n\u2022 Secondary: Hill sprints, accelerations and sprints, CV pace, intermediate 3200m/1600m workouts\n\u2022 Tertiary: easy to moderate mileage, threshold pace, 400m races (as training)\n\nLate-season:\n\u2022 Main: 800m workouts and races\n\u2022 Secondary: 400m workouts, maybe 1600m workouts for endurance-oriented runners\n\u2022 Tertiary: accelerations and sprints, CV pace"},
_general:{title:"Recommended Approach Overall",text:"Obviously I lean much more in the direction of aerobically oriented training, even for 800m though you need some adjustments depending on the athlete.\n\u2022 Not everyone who thinks they are an 800m runner is actually best suited for the 800m!\n\nIn terms of non-workout days, you will find that high schoolers need more 'conditioning runs' or 'maintenance runs', i.e. easy progressing to moderate type runs, or moderate the whole way, as opposed to true recovery runs at a very easy pace.\n\u2022 Part of this is that when you are not in great shape because you didn't train all winter, there is no such thing as a recovery run! Everything is some flavor of moderate, in effect\n\u2022 Another part is that as you progress in your career, you move towards bigger stress and bigger recovery. Adults can often do very high volume and high-quality workouts, e.g. 20 mi at 95% MP or 4-3-2-1k at 10k >> 5k pace, both sessions would be extreme overreach for a high schooler\n  \u25CB Conversely the adult needs VERY easy recovery, often 3\u20135 days, after such tough sessions\n\u2022 For a high schooler, and especially younger high schoolers, you need a 'flatter' distribution of intensity in the week\n  \u25CB Better to do a few low volume sessions every week vs. really hammer one big one\n  \u25CB e.g. contrast adult who might do 10x1k at threshold Monday and 4x2k at 8k pace Thursday with a very easy and an easy run in between\n  \u25CB vs. high schooler who might do 6 x 1k Monday, and 10x2min at 8k pace ('CV') on Wednesday, with a 45-55 min maintenance run at more of a moderate effort on Tuesday.\n\nYou can also mirror this progression in the season itself. Early in the season you want a flatter distribution of intensity; late season when you do race-specific workouts and races, you can take more true easy / recovery days."},
_newrunners:{title:"Adaptations for New/Inexperienced Runners",text:"\u2022 Overall: fewer reps / lower workout volume, and avoid longer repeats (>2 min in duration)\n  \u25CB With poor pacing skills they will not be able to hit paces accurately\n\u2022 Okay to have them do sprints\n\u2022 Do some kind of fitness evaluation to see how speed/endurance oriented they are\n  \u25CB e.g. race 4x400m at JV meet\n\u2022 Can do some ad-hoc work like having a 5:40 miler do mile pace repeats with someone doing CV pace at 5:40/mi, or similar stuff \u2013 as needed / desired, can get a little chaotic but good for giving younger promising runners the experience of running with the faster older runners"},
_progression:{title:"Athlete Progression / Improvement",text:"\u2022 Highly individual of course, in addition to tracking actual race performance you can also track pace improvements in a specific category of workout (e.g. pace for threshold reps or CV reps) \u2013 trickier since it requires more extensive record keeping\n\n\u2022 One general note regarding high schoolers and development, there is a phenomenon I call 'aerobic drift' where high schoolers tend to be worse at longer distances vs. what a conversion chart would predict. This is because they are less aerobically developed \u2013 e.g. if using Daniels' VDOT charts to predict threshold, you probably need to go 1-2 VDOT points slower for a 3200 time, and 2\u20133 points slower for a 1600m time\n  \u25CB This effect is even more pronounced for less-fit / less-experienced athletes\n  \u25CB My own threshold/CV calculator is also affected by this phenomenon because the only high school times I have are from honor rolls, which have an artificial cutoff (and hence exclude the slower runners and those who do not convert up very well)"},
_christiansen:{title:"Comments on Previous Training (Scott Christiansen)",text:"Scott Christiansen has a very heavily Peter Coe-influenced approach; basically low volume, high quality. The five-pace system Coe advocates is basically:\n\u2022 Top speed (e.g. flying 30m or 60m reps with full rest, maximum speed)\n\u2022 400m pace (150m or 200m reps with long rest)\n\u2022 800m pace (200\u2013600m repeats with medium to long rest)\n  \u25CB Maybe also 1500m pace\n\u2022 'VO2max pace' (~3k pace, 800\u20131600m repeats with short rest)\n\u2022 Threshold (~CS- pace, 1k-2k repeats with very short rest, or short continuous tempo runs)\n\u2022 This system only has a modest amount of easy running and no sub-threshold or marathon pace type work, also very little/no work at 5k and 8k/10k pace\n\nThat sort of high intensity system works well for 800m, okay for 1600m in some runners, and very poorly for 3200m and 5k XC.\n\u2022 e.g. compare Edina (aerobically oriented training, lots of 3200m and XC success) and Stillwater (Coe-style training, lots of 800m and 1600m success)"}
};

